<div class="bc"><a onclick="go(0)">Home</a><span>›</span>Where to start</div>

<div class="guide-intro">
  <div class="eys" style="font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:.5rem;">A gentle guide</div>
  <h1>You've just lost someone.<br><em>Here is where to begin.</em></h1>
  <p>The days and weeks after a death can feel overwhelming. There is no single right order of things — but there are people, services, and resources that can help carry the weight. This page explains what each one does, so you can find what fits your situation.</p>
  <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--cl);font-style:italic;">Take your time. You don't have to figure everything out at once.</p>
</div>

<div class="wd" style="background:var(--wh);"></div>
<div class="wu" style="background:var(--tvp);padding:2.5rem 2.5rem 3rem;">
  <div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;">
    <div class="shd" style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
      <div class="eys" style="font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:.35rem;">People who can help</div>
      <h2 class="sh">Services available through CodaCo</h2>
      <p class="st">All providers are vetted. You can search by location.</p>
    </div>

    <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:16px;margin-bottom:2.5rem;">

      <div class="gsc sage" onclick="go(1)">
        <div class="gsc-icon s"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 36 36" fill="none"><circle cx="14" cy="12" r="5" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.6"/><path d="M5 28 C5 22 9 19 14 19 C19 19 23 22 23 28" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"/><path d="M25 16 C25 16 28 14 31 17" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.4" stroke-linecap="round" fill="none"/></svg></div>
        <div><div class="gsc-tagline sg">People support</div><div class="gsc-name">Death doula</div><div class="gsc-desc">A death doula is a trained, non-medical companion who supports the dying person and their family through the emotional, practical, and spiritual dimensions of end of life. They help you understand what's happening, facilitate difficult conversations, sit vigil, and be present in ways that medical staff simply don't have time for. Many doulas also offer bereavement support after a death.</div><div class="gsc-when">When it helps: during an active dying process at home or in a facility; after a sudden death when a family needs presence and guidance; when you feel alone in the process and need someone to help hold it with you.</div><a class="gsc-link sg">Find a death doula near you →</a></div>
      </div>

      <div class="gsc sage" onclick="go(1)">
        <div class="gsc-icon s"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 36 36" fill="none"><circle cx="18" cy="16" r="10" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.6" fill="none"/><path d="M14 16 C14 13 16 11 18 11 C20 11 22 13 22 16" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.4" fill="none"/><line x1="18" y1="22" x2="18" y2="26" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.4" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg></div>
        <div><div class="gsc-tagline sg">Ceremony &amp; tribute</div><div class="gsc-name">Funeral celebrant</div><div class="gsc-desc">A celebrant designs and leads a personalized memorial, funeral, or celebration of life ceremony — entirely tailored to the person who died and the family's wishes. Unlike a religious officiant, a celebrant doesn't require any particular faith tradition. They interview family members, craft a meaningful tribute, and guide the ceremony itself. A good celebrant turns a funeral into a true reflection of a real life.</div><div class="gsc-when">When it helps: when you want a memorial that feels specific to your loved one — not generic; when the family is secular or multi-faith; when a traditional funeral service doesn't feel right.</div><a class="gsc-link sg">Find a celebrant near you →</a></div>
      </div>

      <div class="gsc" onclick="go(1)">
        <div class="gsc-icon t"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 36 36" fill="none"><rect x="8" y="8" width="20" height="20" rx="3" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.6" fill="none"/><line x1="12" y1="15" x2="24" y2="15" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.3"/><line x1="12" y1="19" x2="24" y2="19" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.3"/><line x1="12" y1="23" x2="19" y2="23" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.3"/></svg></div>
        <div><div class="gsc-tagline">Legal &amp; financial</div><div class="gsc-name">Estate attorney</div><div class="gsc-desc">An estate attorney helps you navigate the legal process that follows a death — probate, the transfer of assets, settling debts, filing paperwork, and resolving disputes between heirs. If there is a will, they help execute it. If there isn't one, they help you understand what the law requires. This work can be confusing and time-sensitive; having an attorney prevents costly mistakes.</div><div class="gsc-when">When it helps: as soon as possible after a death — many estate processes have legal deadlines. Essential if there is property, financial accounts, a business, or any complexity in the estate.</div><a class="gsc-link">Find an estate attorney near you →</a></div>
      </div>

      <div class="gsc" onclick="go(1)">
        <div class="gsc-icon t"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 36 36" fill="none"><path d="M8 28 L8 14 L18 8 L28 14 L28 28" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" fill="none"/><rect x="13" y="20" width="10" height="8" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.4"/></svg></div>
        <div><div class="gsc-tagline">Practical &amp; organizational</div><div class="gsc-name">End of life organizer</div><div class="gsc-desc">An EOL organizer helps the family manage the enormous practical load that arrives after a death: notifying institutions, closing accounts, locating documents, handling subscriptions and digital assets, organizing belongings, and coordinating logistics. Think of them as a compassionate project manager for the administrative aftermath — freeing you to grieve without drowning in paperwork.</div><div class="gsc-when">When it helps: in the weeks after a death when the volume of tasks feels unmanageable; when the deceased lived alone or had complex affairs; when family members are geographically scattered.</div><a class="gsc-link">Find an EOL organizer near you →</a></div>
      </div>

      <div class="gsc sage" onclick="go(1)">
        <div class="gsc-icon s"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 36 36" fill="none"><path d="M10 10 L26 10 L26 28 L10 28 Z" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" stroke-linejoin="round"/><line x1="14" y1="16" x2="22" y2="16" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.2"/><line x1="14" y1="20" x2="22" y2="20" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.2"/><line x1="14" y1="24" x2="19" y2="24" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="1.2"/></svg></div>
        <div><div class="gsc-tagline sg">Home &amp; belongings</div><div class="gsc-name">Death cleaning (döstädning)</div><div class="gsc-desc">Döstädning is a Swedish concept — literally "death cleaning" — and refers to the thoughtful sorting and clearing of a person's home and possessions after they die. A professional death cleaner helps families work through a lifetime of belongings with care and sensitivity, deciding what to keep, donate, sell, or let go. This is very different from a standard estate sale or moving company — it's a slower, more intentional process.</div><div class="gsc-when">When it helps: when you need to clear a loved one's home but can't face it alone; when there is too much to deal with practically; when the process feels emotionally too heavy to manage without support.</div><a class="gsc-link sg">Find a death cleaning specialist →</a></div>
      </div>

      <div class="gsc" onclick="go(1)">
        <div class="gsc-icon t"><svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 36 36" fill="none"><path d="M11 8 C11 8 13 10 18 10 C23 10 25 8 25 8 L25 24 C25 27 22 29 18 29 C14 29 11 27 11 24 Z" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/><path d="M14 18 C16 19.5 20 19.5 22 18" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.2" stroke-linecap="round"/></svg></div>
        <div><div class="gsc-tagline">Home care</div><div class="gsc-name">Home funeral guide</div><div class="gsc-desc">In most US states, families have the legal right to care for their own dead at home, without a funeral home. A home funeral guide helps families do exactly that — washing and dressing the body, keeping it at home for a period of visitation and farewell, and arranging direct burial or cremation themselves. This is a deeply intimate option that many families find profoundly healing.</div><div class="gsc-when">When it helps: when a family wants a slow, intimate, home-based farewell rather than handing the body immediately to a funeral home; when cost is a concern; when cultural or spiritual practices call for family involvement in the care of the body.</div><a class="gsc-link">Find a home funeral guide →</a></div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="sec-div"><span>When you're ready — goods that may help</span></div>
    <div class="gd-row" style="margin-top:1.25rem;">
      <div class="gmc" onclick="go(2)"><div class="gmc-icon"><svg width="22" height="26" viewBox="0 0 60 70" fill="none"><path d="M30 8 C18 8 10 20 10 38 C10 52 18 62 30 62 C42 62 50 52 50 38 C50 20 42 8 30 8Z" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="2" fill="none"/></svg></div><div><div class="gmc-name">Urns &amp; vessels</div><div class="gmc-desc">A resting place for cremated remains — handmade, purposeful, lasting. Many can be personalized.</div></div></div>
      <div class="gmc" onclick="go(3)"><div class="gmc-icon" style="background:var(--sp);"><svg width="22" height="26" viewBox="0 0 60 62" fill="none"><path d="M18 58 L18 22 L30 14 L42 22 L42 58" stroke="#7A9E82" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" fill="none"/></svg></div><div><div class="gmc-name">Burial shrouds</div><div class="gmc-desc">Natural, biodegradable wrappings for green or home burial. Dignified and beautiful.</div></div></div>
      <div class="gmc" onclick="go(3)"><div class="gmc-icon" style="background:var(--pl2);"><svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 60 60" fill="none"><path d="M30 10 L33 22 L44 22 L35 28 L38 38 L30 32 L22 38 L25 28 L16 22 L27 22 Z" stroke="#5A534C" stroke-width="1.8" fill="none" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></div><div><div class="gmc-name">Ash jewelry</div><div class="gmc-desc">Memorial pendants and keepsakes that hold cremated remains close.</div></div></div>
      <div class="gmc" onclick="go(3)"><div class="gmc-icon"><svg width="22" height="26" viewBox="0 0 60 70" fill="none"><rect x="12" y="8" width="36" height="52" rx="3" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="2" fill="none"/><line x1="18" y1="22" x2="42" y2="22" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.5"/><line x1="18" y1="30" x2="42" y2="30" stroke="#C1634F" stroke-width="1.5"/></svg></div><div><div class="gmc-name">Planning &amp; legacy docs</div><div class="gmc-desc">Workbooks and templates to capture a loved one's wishes, stories, and important documents.</div></div></div>
    </div>

    <div class="sec-div" style="padding-top:2.25rem;"><span>Reading that might help you right now</span></div>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(240px,1fr));gap:14px;margin-top:1.25rem;">
      <div style="background:var(--wh);border:1px solid rgba(44,40,37,.09);border-radius:10px;padding:1.2rem 1.25rem;display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start;"><div style="width:38px;height:38px;border-radius:6px;background:#8B4F42;flex-shrink:0;"></div><div><div style="font-family:var(--sf);font-size:15px;color:var(--ch);margin-bottom:2px;">Briefly Perfectly Human</div><div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--cl);margin-bottom:6px;">Alua Arthur</div><div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--cm);line-height:1.5;">Written by a death doula, this book is both a memoir and a gentle guide to what it means to be present with dying. Many bereaved readers find it deeply comforting.</div></div></div>
      <div style="background:var(--wh);border:1px solid rgba(44,40,37,.09);border-radius:10px;padding:1.2rem 1.25rem;display:flex;gap:12px;align-items:flex-start;"><div style="width:38px;height:38px;border-radius:6px;background:#4A4030;flex-shrink:0;"></div><div><div style="font-family:var(--sf);font-size:15px;color:var(--ch);margin-bottom:2px;">Being Mortal</div><div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--cl);margin-bottom:6px;">Atul Gawande</div><div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--cm);line-height:1.5;">A physician's honest account of how we die in America and how to reclaim agency in the process. Helpful for anyone navigating decisions in the aftermath of a death.</div></div></div>
    </div>

    <div style="background:var(--tvp);border:1px solid var(--tp);border-radius:12px;padding:1.5rem 1.75rem;margin-top:2rem;text-align:center;">
      <div style="font-family:var(--sf);font-size:24px;font-weight:300;color:var(--ch);margin-bottom:.5rem;">You don't have to do this alone.</div>
      <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--cm);max-width:480px;margin:0 auto 1.25rem;line-height:1.75;">Every provider listed on CodaCo has been vetted. If you're not sure who to contact first, a death doula is often the right starting point — they can help you figure out what else you need.</p>
      <div style="display:flex;gap:12px;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;"><button class="btn-p" onclick="go(1)">Find a death doula near me →</button><button class="btn-s" onclick="go(1)">Browse all services</button></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

